E END--><br>
<br>
Iustus - the point being made applied to attending a guild raid, not applying for a guild membership. The poster is saying that members are not turned away from guild raids because of what class they play.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Perhaps it is the exception, but most of the people in my guild spend most of their online time raiding, not doing exp groups. When your guild raids 10 hours a day or more, there is not a lot of time left over for exp grouping.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not exceptional, nonetheless irrelevant. Your statement, to put it in the context of our discussion is - the solution for warriors struggling to hold aggro in exp groups is...raid 10 hours/day? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What I said was if you assume that you cannot be perfect, and get them 100% balanced, then it makes sense to make one better at raids and the other better in exp groups, rather than one class better at both.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
To reiterate - desirability at raids and desirability at exp groups are 2 completely different issues. If the knights feel they are not needed in raid situations to the same level as warriors, then start a separate thread addressing the issue. But don't tell me and my exp group that warrior taunt won't be fixed because I can tank on raids. Because that is what you are saying. You cannot draw a parallel between raid desiribility and xp grouping. They are 2 radically different activities.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I do not see that as the problem. A good knight being chosen over a good warrior is ok, they are both good players. The problem is when a bad knight is chosen over a good warrior. Or if a group doesnt want to take a chance on a warrior, because the good ones are too rare. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Define good. If good is defined as able to hold aggro over slow and tash cast on an incoming mob, then a whole lotta warriors are in big trouble....<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>This is why I said the test should be a comparison between a bad person of one and a good one of the other<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :eek --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eek.gif ALT=":eek"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  The functionality of a test is to get as many variables equal to assess the importance of the attribute being tested. The attribute in question is warrior aggro vs paladin aggro - so you want 2 players of equal level and equipment in the exact same environment  to assess the relative use of both. Saying that 'warrior taunt is ok' because it was tested between a 'good' warrior and a 'bad' paladin is ludicrous in the extreme. Good and bad are in any event completely arbitrary assessments - how does one define that exactly?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>It is my suspicion that a warrior significantly more dps than at least a paladin tanking. I know I give up dps in order to tank. Yes, we can cast stuns between swings, but with the fast weapons of today, that is hard to time, and with a lot going on, usually low on my priority list<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
DPS is irelevant to tanking - a tanks job is to BE hit, not DEAL damage. But in any event, 2handers are better DPS than dual wield and paladins can use them, admittedly with a lower offense cap. So the result might not be as favourable to a warrior as you may be thinking. Galtius' point about group DPS is very valid though. And how exactly as a paladin are you holding aggro if stuns are low on your list of priorities? <br>
