 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iustus>Iustus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/10/03 7:04 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: no Glatius</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Desirability in an exp group determines if you will get to do anything with your time online, when did anyone get turned away from a guild raid because they were 'not the most desirable class'?<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Iustus - the point being made applied to attending a guild raid, not applying for a guild membership. The poster is saying that members are not turned away from guild raids because of what class they play.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
My point was to illustrate the some classes are less useful on raids, and sometimes feel completely useless. Of course no one who is already guilded is going to get turned down for a guild raid. I do not see that ever happening, no matter how bad a class is. That is just not how guilds work. However, guilds can and do refuse to guild any new people if they consider that class not useful. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Perhaps it is the exception, but most of the people in my guild spend most of their online time raiding, not doing exp groups. When your guild raids 10 hours a day or more, there is not a lot of time left over for exp grouping.<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Not exceptional, nonetheless irrelevant. Your statement, to put it in the context of our discussion is - the solution for warriors struggling to hold aggro in exp groups is...raid 10 hours/day? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
No, my point was to give a counterexample to the person who said that raids did not matter because most of his online time was spent in exp groups. Most of my online time is spent raiding. Which brings us to the following point.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Quote:<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
What I said was if you assume that you cannot be perfect, and get them 100% balanced, then it makes sense to make one better at raids and the other better in exp groups, rather than one class better at both.<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
To reiterate - desirability at raids and desirability at exp groups are 2 completely different issues. If the knights feel they are not needed in raid situations to the same level as warriors, then start a separate thread addressing the issue. But don't tell me and my exp group that warrior taunt won't be fixed because I can tank on raids. Because that is what you are saying. You cannot draw a parallel between raid desiribility and xp grouping. They are 2 radically different activities.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
They may be different activities, but they are both part of the experience of playing Everquest. To say that you can ignore one while trying to balance the other is to not take the whole picture into account. This is how wild imbalances occur. You have to account for both desirablity while raiding and in exp groups. This probably will mean that some classes are better in exp groups and others are better on raids. I will ask again, would you be willing to swap places with knights, being better than knights in exp groups, but less desireable than knights on raids?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Define good. If good is defined as able to hold aggro over slow and tash cast on an incoming mob, then a whole lotta warriors are in big trouble....<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Good is defined as being skilled at playing your class. Good is knowing when to use the taunt key to be most effective. Good is knowing how and when to use /shield to be most effective. Good is good enough so that an exp group feels like you are a real benefit to have in the group.<br>
<br>
We are not talking about an emperical test of comparison. That very idea is impossible. There are way too many variables to assess, most of which are subjective. We are talking about desirability in groups of both classes. You simply cannot reduce the problem to which class can hold agro the best, and then try to even it out. The fact that knights can gain agro better than warriors is one of the strengths of knights, to balance out their weaknesses. <br>
<br>
Class balance is a big picture thing. You cannot reduce it to the one point where you are weak and say fix just that.<br>
<br>
And so therefore, dps is a valid thing in a group, because more dps means mobs die faster. Now the point that it is possible overall group dps goes down, because they might have to hold back more with a warrior, is a good one. If this is the case, if good warriors really cannot hold agro, then that certainly should be addressed.<br>
<br>
I would like to make one final point. That knights can hold agro better than a warrior is nothing new. It is not something that changed in PoP. It was true back at level 30 when I got my first stun in 1999, and is true today. It might be true that holding agro is more important now, perhaps because mobs hit so much harder, but the fact that knights can gain and hold agro better has always been true in EQ. It has been a signature of the knight classes for longer than warriors have had defensive.<br>
<br>
-I <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=124361">Duke Iustus</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
Lord Protector of Marr<br>
Tarew Marr<br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 910<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/10/03 10:24 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: no Glatius</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Good is defined as being skilled at playing your class. Good is knowing when to use the taunt key to be most effective. Good is knowing how and when to use /shield to be most effective. Good is good enough so that an exp group feels like you are a real benefit to have in the group.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If during Kunark I had said that the problem wasn't with the Paladin class, the problem was whether or not the player running the Paladin was a good player, how might you have reacted?  I'm thinking you wouldn't have taken that too well.  In fact, you might find it somewhat insulting.  Sort of like I do with your implication that if a Warrior sees problems with initial aggro control, they might be or must be a poor player.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>We are not talking about an emperical test of comparison. That very idea is impossible. There are way too many variables to assess, most of which are subjective. We are talking about desirability in groups of both classes. You simply cannot reduce the problem to which class can hold agro the best, and then try to even it out. The fact that knights can gain agro better than warriors is one of the strengths of knights, to balance out their weaknesses.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Indeed.  So by this concept, since Warrior HP is one of their great strengths and one of the things that a group will select them for, it would seem reasonable that they should have considerably more than a Paladin, much as the Paladin has considerably more initial aggro.  It would make sense that the Warriors should be using their strength to perform the same function Paladins are using their strength, obtain and hold aggro.  <br>
<br>
Therefore, since it takes about 10 seconds for a Warrior to gain and establish aggro, while a Paladin can do so instantly, Warriors should have enough HP more than a Paladin in the same gear that they can stand up to an unslowed mob for 10  seconds and not drop below the value of HP a Paladin would have in the same situation.  What is the rough DPS of most common mobs in PoP?  500 DPS?  More?  Less?  The Warrior should be able to stand up against an unslowed mob every single battle for the duration specified without danger of dying.  So the Warrrior should have something like 5000HP more than a Paladin, right?  That would be playing to our strengths.  However that amount of HP is far beyond what 90% of the Warrior population will ever see. As a result, the aggro difference will need to change.  The time required to gain aggro should be short enough that the Warrior can gain aggro in the time frame his HP advantage will allow so that the slower can slow.  Not instantly, but quickly enough that he only loses 1k or so, about what he would normally have more than a Paladin.  To do otherwise would skew the game too dramatically in other ways.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Class balance is a big picture thing. You cannot reduce it to the one point where you are weak and say fix just that.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
But yet your alternative solution would be to tell everyone who plays a Warrior, unless you're raiding a majority of your time, forget about enjoying your character or getting a group.  The Knights don't add as much value on a raid, therefore they get the groups and you get to log.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>And so therefore, dps is a valid thing in a group, because more dps means mobs die faster. Now the point that it is possible overall group dps goes down, because they might have to hold back more with a warrior, is a good one. If this is the case, if good warriors really cannot hold agro, then that certainly should be addressed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And how exactly can the DPS not be greater?  If, as has clearly been established, a slower can slow immediately upon a mob getting in range with a Knight tank, how can you not have other people able to do other things sooner as well?  Please explain how stuns can negate slow aggro and yet not allow a Rogue to BS more, a Wizard to nuke sooner, and so on?  Logically, you can't.  It's impossible.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I would like to make one final point. That knights can hold agro better than a warrior is nothing new. It is not something that changed in PoP. It was true back at level 30 when I got my first stun in 1999, and is true today. It might be true that holding agro is more important now, perhaps because mobs hit so much harder, but the fact that knights can gain and hold agro better has always been true in EQ. It has been a signature of the knight classes for longer than warriors have had defensive.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes we know.  And prior to PoP it wasn't that significant a problem.  Because the common experience mobs in previous expansions had no where near the DPS of PoP mobs.  Wouldn't you consider that a pretty obvious fact?  That being the case, aggro control in the first few seconds of the common experience encounter is much more important than in any previous expansion.  I would consider this also to be pretty obvious.  How could you go expansion after expansion with initial aggro control not being that important and then in one expansion have it jump to the top of the importance list if in fact the expansion hadn't caused the change?<br>
<br>
