Val <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=krazrussian>KrazRussian</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 125<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/11/03 7:00 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: no Glatius</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;We are not talking about an emperical test of comparison. That very idea is impossible. There are way too many variables to assess, most of which are subjective. We are talking about desirability in groups of both classes. You simply cannot reduce the problem to which class can hold agro the best, and then try to even it out. The fact that knights can gain agro better than warriors is one of the strengths of knights, to balance out their weaknesses. &quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Just out of curiosity, what are these weaknesses you are talking about? The 4% difference in avoidance caps that amounts to about 1.5% less damage, an amount easily surmoutable by paladin healing ability? The HP difference that is surmountable whenever a group has no cleric? The offensive skill cap differences that will amount to all of 100atk rating? The 3-minute plunder disc which is used in XP groups as &quot;emergency-only,&quot; much like your own heals and LoH? Do you honestly mean to tell me that you believe these minute differences are balanced against the virtual inability to achieve initial agro in a group, thereby making knights far superior as XP tanks? If honestly believe this, then you are no different than the warriors who claimed knights were just fine in RoK/SoV.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;I would like to make one final point. That knights can hold agro better than a warrior is nothing new. It is not something that changed in PoP. It was true back at level 30 when I got my first stun in 1999, and is true today. It might be true that holding agro is more important now, perhaps because mobs hit so much harder, but the fact that knights can gain and hold agro better has always been true in EQ. It has been a signature of the knight classes for longer than warriors have had defensive.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
True, it has. However, until recently, the defensive skill cap differences between knights and warriors were more significant. We had separate offensive damage tables. Our mitigation was better (it isn't now). Our AC was better back when it really mattered. Duel-wielding was better than 2-handed weapons. None of this is true anymore. We share the same offensive tables, 2-handers are WAYY better than d-wield, the defensive skill caps are much narrower, we have equal damage mitigation, AC differences between warriors and knights have decreased, not to mention higher AC has very diminishing returns. <br>
<br>
All the above changes have been in favor of knights. All have come within the last 2 years. Can you show me what has changed about the warrior class in that time? Don't ask, I'll tell you; nothing significant. Couple this with the fact that the role of taunt in XP groups has increased massively in significance, becoming far more important than minor mitigation differences. How do you justify this?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;And so therefore, dps is a valid thing in a group, because more dps means mobs die faster. Now the point that it is possible overall group dps goes down, because they might have to hold back more with a warrior, is a good one. If this is the case, if good warriors really cannot hold agro, then that certainly should be addressed.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This IS the issue we're talking about. Good warriors cannot hold agro. The suppressed group DPS with warriors tanking instead of knights is far greater than any DPS differences between knights and wars.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;We are not talking about an emperical test of comparison. That very idea is impossible. There are way too many variables to assess, most of which are subjective. We are talking about desirability in groups of both classes. You simply cannot reduce the problem to which class can hold agro the best, and then try to even it out. The fact that knights can gain agro better than warriors is one of the strengths of knights, to balance out their weaknesses. &quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
You can when agro is really the lone important factor in determining which is the preferred tank class. There is NO significant difference between knight and warrior tanking ability in Xp areas. Both classes have the HP and tanking ability to fulfill the role, but warriors lack agro ability, while knights have it in plentiful supply. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Class balance is a big picture thing. You cannot reduce it to the one point where you are weak and say fix just that.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is your standard knight beat around the bush response. Are there minute factors in subsequent areas involved in the whole knight vs. war in XP groups? Yes. Do these factors matter? NO. It's simple, in PoP, because of the greater demand for sufficient agro ability, Taunt is the only factor that needs to be addressed. Everything else, the minute diferences are insignificant, even when added up. The bottom line is simple, we have @#%$ agro ability in a time when Agro &gt; all. This needs to be fixed, very simple.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;They may be different activities, but they are both part of the experience of playing Everquest. To say that you can ignore one while trying to balance the other is to not take the whole picture into account. This is how wild imbalances occur. You have to account for both desirablity while raiding and in exp groups. This probably will mean that some classes are better in exp groups and others are better on raids. I will ask again, would you be willing to swap places with knights, being better than knights in exp groups, but less desireable than knights on raids?&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ah, the raid issue. This other fallacious argument hanging on by a small ripping threads that knights always bring up to impede any warriors fixes. Tell me, which class is more important on raids, wizards or rogues? Clerics or shamans? Answer; they are all important in different roles. Same goes for warriors and knights. Yep, knights don't usually MT on a raid; thats the warrior role. However, knights have their own purposes, notably in add-tanking because of their superior initial agro abilities, BSS and heals in the case of paladins (you can't tell me that pally group heals aren't useful in an AoE mob fight), or FD and agro-increasing spells brought by SK's. O<br>
<br>
n raids, knight roles are fare more versatile. Yes, a tanking warrior is more important than a knight, but you only need a couple of warriors to serve as tanks. However, knights are FAR more useful to a raid than non-tanking warriors. So, your claim that warrior superiority in a raid balances their inferiority as XP tanks is pure and utter <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>BULLSH!T</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. After all, if you're gonna travel down that road, I could use the argument that SK solo ability, and paladin solo ability is &gt; warriors ability, therefore they must serve as inferior XP tanks.   <br>
